content.text:
Every single removed message, one line each. Look at **lines 218-234** of `compact.rs`:

```rust
lines.push("- Key timeline:".to_string());
for message in messages {
    let role = match message.role {
        MessageRole::System => "system",
        MessageRole::User => "user",
        MessageRole::Assistant => "assistant",
        MessageRole::Tool => "tool",
    };
    let content = message
        .blocks
        .iter()
        .map(summarize_block)
        .collect::<Vec<_>>()
        .join(" | ");
    lines.push(format!("  - {role}: {content}"));
}
```

It iterates over **all removed messages** and for each one writes `role: block summaries`. The block summaries come from `summarize_block()` at **line 273**:

```rust
fn summarize_block(block: &ContentBlock) -> String {
    let raw = match block {
        ContentBlock::Text { text } => text.clone(),
        ContentBlock::ToolUse { name, input, .. } => format!("tool_use {name}({input})"),
        ContentBlock::ToolResult { tool_name, output, is_error, .. } => format!(
            "tool_result {tool_name}: {}{output}",
            if *is_error { "error " } else { "" }
        ),
    };
    truncate_summary(&raw, 160)
}
```

Each block is truncated to **160 characters**. Multiple blocks in one message are joined with `" | "`.

So for the 6 removed messages from the earlier example, the timeline would look like:

```
- Key timeline:
  - user: find TODOs
  - assistant: Let me search for TODO comments. | tool_use grep_search({"pattern":"TODO","path":"src/"})
  - tool: tool_result grep_search: src/auth.rs:10: // TODO: validate\nsrc/lib.rs:42: // TODO: cleanup
  - assistant: tool_use read_file({"path":"src/auth.rs"})
  - tool: tool_result read_file: line 9: fn check_token(t: &str) {\nline 10: // TODO: validate\nline 11: }
  - assistant: tool_use edit_file({"path":"src/auth.rs","old":"// TODO: validate","new":"validate_token(t)"})
```

It's a compressed but complete chronological log of everything that was removed вАФ roles, tool names, inputs, outputs, all truncated to 160 chars per block. Not a smart summary, just a mechanical flattening.

