No. Subagents have no hooks.

`build_agent_runtime()` at `tools/lib.rs:3155` calls `ConversationRuntime::new()`, which uses `RuntimeFeatureConfig::default()` internally (`conversation.rs:154-161`):

```rust
pub fn new(...) -> Self {
    Self::new_with_features(
        ...,
        &RuntimeFeatureConfig::default(),  // вЖР default = no hooks
    )
}
```

The default `RuntimeFeatureConfig` has an empty `RuntimeHookConfig` вАФ all three lists (`pre_tool_use`, `post_tool_use`, `post_tool_use_failure`) are empty `Vec`s. So `run_commands()` at `hooks.rs:320-322` returns immediately:

```rust
if commands.is_empty() {
    return HookRunResult::allow(Vec::new());
}
```

The parent runtime's hooks are configured via `new_with_features()` which receives the user's loaded config. But the subagent constructs its own `ConversationRuntime` from scratch with no config pass-through. The user's hook configuration doesn't propagate.

