Here's a concrete example of what gets sent to Anthropic at **iteration 3** of the Harry Styles session you showed me. This is the exact JSON structure produced by `MessageRequest` serialization:

```json
{
  "model": "claude-sonnet-4-20250514",
  "max_tokens": 8096,
  "stream": true,
  "system": "You are an interactive agent that helps users...\n\n# System\n - All text you output...\n\n# Doing tasks\n...\n\n# Environment context\n - Working directory: /Users/gladyscavero/...\n...",
  "tools": [
    {
      "name": "WebSearch",
      "description": "Search the web for information.",
      "input_schema": {
        "type": "object",
        "properties": {
          "query": { "type": "string" }
        },
        "required": ["query"]
      }
    },
    {
      "name": "WebFetch",
      "description": "Fetch a URL and return its contents.",
      "input_schema": { "..." }
    }
  ],
  "tool_choice": { "type": "auto" },
  "messages": [
    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": [
        { "type": "text", "text": "Investigate who is harry styles" }
      ]
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": [
        { "type": "text", "text": "\n\nHarry Styles is a well-known public figure. Let me search for current information about him." },
        { "type": "tool_use", "id": "toolu_015LDrR86cebs7wnkYmA5c68", "name": "WebSearch", "input": { "query": "Who is Harry Styles" } }
      ]
    },
    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": [
        { "type": "tool_result", "tool_use_id": "toolu_015LDrR86cebs7wnkYmA5c68", "content": [{ "type": "text", "text": "{\n  \"query\": \"Who is Harry Styles\",\n  \"results\": [...]\n}" }], "is_error": false }
      ]
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": [
        { "type": "tool_use", "id": "toolu_01P7KwXnFTFfij591Q6txBT5", "name": "WebFetch", "input": { "url": "https://www.britannica.com/biography/Harry-Styles", "prompt": "Give me a comprehensive biography..." } }
      ]
    },
    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": [
        { "type": "tool_result", "tool_use_id": "toolu_01P7KwXnFTFfij591Q6txBT5", "content": [{ "type": "text", "text": "{\n  \"bytes\": 105684,\n  \"code\": 200,\n  \"result\": \"Fetched https://www.britannica.com/...\"}" }], "is_error": false }
      ]
    }
  ]
}
```

### The key things to see

**`system`** вАФ a single string, separate from messages. The `Vec<String>` segments are joined with `"\n\n"` (`main.rs:4533`).

**`tools`** вАФ the full tool catalog with JSON schemas. Sent on every request, unchanged.

**`messages`** вАФ strict `"user"` / `"assistant"` alternation:

| What it was in the runtime | What the API sees | Content block type |
|---|---|---|
| `MessageRole::User` | `"role": "user"` | `"type": "text"` |
| `MessageRole::Assistant` (text) | `"role": "assistant"` | `"type": "text"` |
| `MessageRole::Assistant` (tool call) | `"role": "assistant"` | `"type": "tool_use"` |
| `MessageRole::Tool` | `"role": "user"` | `"type": "tool_result"` |
| `MessageRole::System` (compaction) | `"role": "user"` | `"type": "text"` |

The API distinguishes tool results from user messages not by role (both are `"user"`) but by the **content block type** вАФ `"tool_result"` with a `"tool_use_id"` that matches the assistant's `"tool_use"` block's `"id"`.

It looks exactly like any other tool call. The `Agent` tool isn't special at the API level. Here's what iteration 2 would look like if the model called an Agent in iteration 1:

```json
{
  "model": "claude-sonnet-4-20250514",
  "max_tokens": 8096,
  "stream": true,
  "system": "You are an interactive agent...",
  "tools": [
    { "name": "Agent", "description": "Launch a specialized agent task...", "input_schema": { "..." } },
    { "name": "Read", "..." },
    { "name": "Bash", "..." }
  ],
  "tool_choice": { "type": "auto" },
  "messages": [
    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": [
        { "type": "text", "text": "Explore this repo and tell me how the permission system works" }
      ]
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": [
        { "type": "text", "text": "I'll launch an agent to explore the codebase." },
        {
          "type": "tool_use",
          "id": "toolu_01ABC123",
          "name": "Agent",
          "input": {
            "description": "Explore permission system",
            "prompt": "Read the runtime crate and explain how permissions work...",
            "subagent_type": "Explore"
          }
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "tool_result",
          "tool_use_id": "toolu_01ABC123",
          "content": [{
            "type": "text",
            "text": "{\n  \"agentId\": \"agent-1775496752780-42\",\n  \"name\": \"explore-permission-system\",\n  \"description\": \"Explore permission system\",\n  \"subagentType\": \"Explore\",\n  \"model\": \"claude-sonnet-4-20250514\",\n  \"status\": \"running\",\n  \"outputFile\": \".claw/agents/agent-1775496752780-42.md\",\n  \"manifestFile\": \".claw/agents/agent-1775496752780-42.json\",\n  \"createdAt\": \"2026-04-06T18:30:00Z\",\n  \"startedAt\": \"2026-04-06T18:30:00Z\"\n}"
          }],
          "is_error": false
        }
      ]
    }
  ]
}
```

### What the parent model sees

The tool result is just the `AgentOutput` manifest JSON as a string. Note **`"status": "running"`** вАФ the subagent is still working on its own thread. The parent model has no idea what the subagent is doing, what tools it called, or what it found. It only got a receipt.

### What the parent model does next

At this point the model has to decide. It might:

**Option A** вАФ Read the output file to get the subagent's result (if it's done):
```json
{
  "role": "assistant",
  "content": [
    { "type": "tool_use", "id": "toolu_01DEF456", "name": "Read",
      "input": { "file_path": ".claw/agents/agent-1775496752780-42.md" } }
  ]
}
```

**Option B** вАФ Do other work in parallel and check later.

**Option C** вАФ Just summarize based on what it already knows, without waiting.

### What the subagent's API calls look like (separate, invisible to parent)

The subagent has its own `ConversationRuntime` on a separate thread, making its own API calls to Anthropic. Its iteration 1:

```json
{
  "model": "claude-sonnet-4-20250514",
  "max_tokens": 8096,
  "system": "You are an interactive agent...\n\nYou are a background sub-agent of type `Explore`. Work only on the delegated task, use only the tools available to you, do not ask the user questions, and finish with a concise result.",
  "tools": [
    { "name": "Read", "..." },
    { "name": "Glob", "..." },
    { "name": "Grep", "..." }
  ],
  "messages": [
    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": [
        { "type": "text", "text": "Read the runtime crate and explain how permissions work..." }
      ]
    }
  ]
}
```

Note the differences from the parent:
- **Different system prompt** вАФ has the extra line "You are a background sub-agent of type `Explore`..." (`tools/lib.rs:3173-3175`)
- **Restricted tools** вАФ only the tools allowed for that subagent type via `allowed_tools_for_subagent()`, no `Agent` tool (can't spawn sub-sub-agents)
- **Fresh session** вАФ starts with just the prompt as the user message, no parent history
- **No hooks** вАФ default `RuntimeFeatureConfig`
- **Completely separate HTTP calls** вАФ the parent's API calls and the subagent's API calls are independent requests to Anthropic

### The two never mix

The parent's `messages` array never contains the subagent's internal conversation. The subagent's `messages` array never contains the parent's history. They share nothing except the filesystem (the `.claw/agents/` directory where the subagent writes its output).

We already saw this at `tools/lib.rs:3164-3177`:

```rust
fn build_agent_system_prompt(subagent_type: &str) -> Result<Vec<String>, String> {
    let cwd = std::env::current_dir().map_err(|error| error.to_string())?;
    let mut prompt = load_system_prompt(
        cwd,
        DEFAULT_AGENT_SYSTEM_DATE.to_string(),
        std::env::consts::OS,
        "unknown",
    )
    .map_err(|error| error.to_string())?;
    prompt.push(format!(
        "You are a background sub-agent of type `{subagent_type}`. Work only on the delegated task, use only the tools available to you, do not ask the user questions, and finish with a concise result."
    ));
    Ok(prompt)
}
```

It's **the same system prompt as the parent** (`load_system_prompt` builds the same segments вАФ intro, system, doing tasks, actions, environment, CLAUDE.md files) plus **one extra line** appended at the end, parameterized by `subagent_type`.

Let me check what the subagent types are and what tools each gets.

